    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Forget Washington. The Poor Cope Alone'' (front page, Sept. 26):</p>
        <p>New census figures released the other day show that poverty has declined nationwide. However, if one reads the smaller print, this decrease came from metropolitan areas. In Appalachia, the Mississippi Delta and most Indian reservations, poverty is endemic and intractable. There, in some cases, we find children living with no plumbing, no electricity, no heat, no books and little hope for the future.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Forget Washington. The Poor Cope Alone'' (front page, Sept. 26):</p>
        <p>New census figures released the other day show that poverty has declined nationwide. However, if one reads the smaller print, this decrease came from metropolitan areas. In Appalachia, the Mississippi Delta and most Indian reservations, poverty is endemic and intractable. There, in some cases, we find children living with no plumbing, no electricity, no heat, no books and little hope for the future.</p>
        <p>We must marshal our government, private and nonprofit resources in a coordinated effort to provide children in rural America with the same opportunities as their counterparts in the cities and suburbs.</p>
        <p>CATHERINE MILTON  Westport, Conn., Sept. 28, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is executive director of U.S. programs, Save the Children.</p>
      </block>
